<body>
    <theorem>
        Theorem: Every prime number (greater than 2) modulo 4 can be written in the form 4n + 1 or 4n + 3.
    </theorem>

    <proof>
        Proof: Any number p when divided by 4 leaves remainder 0, 1, 2, or 3. Therefore, the number has the form 4n, 4n + 1, 4n + 2, or 4n + 3.
        Since 4n and 4n + 2 are even, so these cannot be a form of a prime number which is an odd number (except 2).
        This proves the theorem.
        <square>â—»</square>
    </proof>
